            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_27gc' title='Col. 27GC &mdash; HL Deb 10 December 2001 vol 629 c27GC' name='column_27gc' href='#column_27gc' rel='bookmark'>27GC</a>
            I stated, is now less subjective, as the noble Baroness acknowledges. Secondly, it is applicant specific. Thirdly&#x2014;and this is not a change in legal principle&#x2014;the authority is obliged to act reasonably in the context of <span class="italic">Wednesbury</span> reasonableness; it would have had to have done so before but the obligation is different.</p><p>
            The final question was about the guidance. The guidance is not part of the statute but if a local authority acts flagrantly against the terms of the guidance, it would be relevant material in considering whether or not the local authority had acted <span class="italic">Wednesbury</span> reasonable.
          </p>
